'''Christopher Nyaole "Chris" Jafta''' (born 1959<ref name=cc />) is a South African judge who currently serves on the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]].<ref name=cc>{{cite web |url=http://www.constitutionalcourt.org.za/site/judges/justicejafta/index1.html |title=Justice Chris Jafta |publisher=Constitutional Court |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>

Froneman grew up in [[Matatiele]] and was educated at the [[University of Transkei]]. He worked as a court interpreter, prosecutor and [[Magistrate (South Africa)|magistrate]], later returning to his alma mater as a lecturer. In 1993 he was admitted as an [[advocate (South Africa)|advocate]].<ref name=cc />

In 1999 he was appointed a judge of the [[Transkei Division]] of the [[High Court of South Africa|High Court]] (now known as the [[Eastern Cape High Court, Mthatha]]). From 2001 to 2003 he was acting Judge President of the Transkei Division, and in 2003 and 2004 he served in acting positions on the [[Labour Appeal Court of South Africa|Labour Appeal Court]] and the [[Supreme Court of Appeal of South Africa|Supreme Court of Appeal]]. In 2004 he was elevated to a permanent position on the Supreme Court of Appeal.<ref name=cc />

In 2007 and 2008 he served as an acting justice of the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa|Constitutional Court]], and in 2009 he was appointed to a permanent term on the court by President [[Jacob Zuma]].<ref name=cc />

